The black and green palette you’ve chosen (#12191B and #05CD77) is a great choice for a web developer portfolio. It gives a modern, high-tech, and professional feel, especially when used as a gradient. The dark background provides depth, while the vibrant green adds contrast and energy. This combination works well for a sleek, futuristic aesthetic, particularly in a dark mode layout.

The fonts you’ve selected—Bricolage Grotesque, Inter, and Libre—are strong choices. Inter is excellent for readability in body text, while Bricolage Grotesque and Libre add uniqueness and character, making headings and key sections stand out.

Suggestions for Enhancing the Palette:
Introduce a Third Accent Color:
To prevent the design from feeling too monochrome, you could add a complementary accent:

Neon blue (#00A3E0) – Enhances the futuristic look and pairs well with green.
Muted yellow (#FFC857) – Adds warmth and contrast, making CTAs pop.
Electric purple (#8A2BE2) – Creates a cyberpunk aesthetic if you want a bolder touch.
Refine the Gradient for Depth:
Instead of a simple linear gradient, try:

Radial gradient: Center the green in a focal area (e.g., behind your name/logo) to create a glowing effect.
Angular gradient: Adds a subtle motion effect, making sections more dynamic.
Example gradient variations:

background: linear-gradient(135deg, #12191B, #05CD77);
background: radial-gradient(circle, #05CD77 10%, #12191B 90%);
Slight Adjustments to Green for Softer Contrast:
If #05CD77 feels too bright, consider slightly desaturating it:

#0ABE6B – A more balanced, softer green.
#04A267 – Darker and more elegant, for a premium look.
Alternative Font Pairings (If You Want Variations):

Space Grotesk – A sharp, futuristic alternative to Bricolage Grotesque for headings.
Sora – A geometric, sleek font that pairs well with Inter.


